<br>
In that case, the Earth threatened with either physical or social ruin, outer space could offer a refuge for a remnant of civilization. A community large enough to be viable, with the huge array of material necessary for it to be self-sustaining, would require a lift capacity far beyond that of any existing booster, or any possible combination that could be assembled at short notice. <br>
<br>
Our governments invest a great deal in preparing for catastrophic contingencies. There are shelters for high officials, elaborate relief and recovery plans, and any number of contingency studies. Wouldn't it make sense to also have Orion ready as an ultimate ace-in-the-hole? <br>
<br>
This would not necessarily have to be a fully assembled ship waiting at some remote site, though I would not be entirely amazed to learn that such a thing actually exists somewhere. Orion is fairly straightforward technically and does not require the super-specialized construction methods normally associated with space systems. A completely researched design, with components and payload stockpiled or standing by, might be assembled in fairly short order, even under desperate circumstances. Having the necessary design and planning already done, though, would take years off the required time and might make all the difference.<br>
<br>
Selecting the payload for a self-sustaining community would be a daunting task, but Orion's lack of severe weight restrictions would simplify it a great deal. That is, extremely specialized research and development would be less necessary if we weren't trying to shave the last ounce from what would necessarily have to be very robust and reliable components, like shelters and machinery. A great deal of research has gone into space habitats over the decades and this is all available for planning and payload selection. <br>
<br>
The choice of crew for such a thing is, of course, a frequent concern of science fiction writers. This is an interesting subject in its own right, but it has been addressed many times over the past century or so. I am confident that suitable people could be found and gotten aboard if it comes to that.<br>
Similarly, I won't go into a choice of destination, since this is a subject of daily discussion among space colonization proponents. <br>
