,  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2039<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/9/02 4:55:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=387.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Designing the  Orion starship</span><hr size=1> Over the years I have begun to question the history of Orion.<br>
<br>
It was never a very well known program. Early media coverage was scanty and important details had to be kept out of the public domain due to the nuclear weapon technology involved. Always a classified project, it could very easily have been upgraded to top secret. Such a small step would not have been difficult. It may in fact have become a black project that has continued until today. Why? Military potential. The more I think about it the more it makes sense. Orion was the most powerful engine concievable with 60's technology(and today's). Where might that program have led if it had never been cancelled?<br>
<br>
The original team members were interested in space exploration. I doubt Freeman Dyson would have been interested in participating in an Orion weapon program. Transferring the work to a new team and letting the original work dissipate quietly would be exactly how I would do it. Dyson might have been wrong when he stated that Orion was the first time progress had been murdered by politics. Progress may have been hidden because of politics.<br>
<br>
What would Orion look like today? I'm guessing and you can think of this as an alternate history if you like, but its as plausible as my limited engineering knowledge can manage.<br>
<br>
Early Orion design required massive shock absorbers and a heavy plate to withstand the shockwaves of small pulse units. Ted Taylor is known to have designed the smallest fission devices in history. If the program had continued then the devices would have become even smaller. Using increasingly innovative ways of reducing both size and yield. Computers might have been used to guide the test craft. Thereby further eliminating much of the need for shock absorption, shielding and a crew section situated far from the detonations.<br>
<br>
Imagine this work continued over nearly 2 generations. Thirty seven years of increasingly smaller pulse units. Better mechanical systems. Smaller more efficient shock absorbing systems not pneumatically based. More aerodynamic design. How would such a thing look? The plate would still be there. Probably making up most of the vehicle. Perhaps it would look something like this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.qtm.net/~geibdan/nlook1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah. It could be a frizbee or a hubcap but it also corresponds to how I imagine the shape of an incredibly advanced Orion to be. One that uses microfission pulses, detonating so rapidly they appear as a single light at the centre of its base. A common report in fact among those who claim to have witnessed saucer shaped flying objects. Such small detonations would still create some EMP. Certainly enough to mess up nearby electrical systems. A phenomenon also commonly associated with Unidentified Flying Objects. Note the small half sphere at the top which could, if it were an Orion, be the habitation or control centre. Perhaps full of water to withstand the vibration from pulses. Astronauts controlling the craft from a floating cockpit. Maybe they are simply remote controlled or computer guided. The rest exactly fits the description of a pusher plate. The ideal shape in fact. Round, thick centred and tapering towards the edges. <br>
<br>
Coincidence? Maybe these people who see strange lights in the sky performing impossible maneuvres at incredible speeds aren't wacko's after all. Just maybe they are witnesses to advanced nuclear flight vehicles being tested.<br>
<br>
